1190.description:
Service: Data Export Service
Feature: CSV Download
User Action: Exporting customer data to CSV

**PROBLEM:**

Clicking "Export to CSV" button downloads file immediately but file is empty (0 bytes). No error shown to user. Export appears successful.

Error in server logs: "File not found: /tmp/export_abc123.csv"

**WHAT'S HAPPENING:**
• Export button triggers async job
• Download starts before job completes
• File doesn't exist yet when download attempted
• Job completes 2-3 seconds later
• File exists but user already downloaded empty file

**AFFECTED:**
Export service, job queue, file storage

---

**WHY:**

Export controller returned download URL immediately after queuing job. Frontend downloaded file before background job finished generating it. Race condition between job completion and download initiation.

Code flow:
1. User clicks export → Job queued → URL returned
2. Browser downloads URL → File doesn't exist yet → Empty file
3. Job completes 2s later → File created → Too late

**FIX:**

Changed to polling-based approach:

```javascript
// BEFORE:
app.post('/export', async (req, res) => {
  const jobId = await queueExportJob(req.body);
  const fileUrl = `/downloads/${jobId}.csv`;
  res.json({ downloadUrl: fileUrl });
});

// AFTER:
app.post('/export', async (req, res) => {
  const jobId = await queueExportJob(req.body);
  res.json({ jobId: jobId });
});

app.get('/export/:jobId/status', async (req, res) => {
  const job = await getJobStatus(req.params.jobId);
  if (job.status === 'completed') {
    res.json({ 
      status: 'ready',
      downloadUrl: `/downloads/${job.fileId}.csv` 
    });
  } else {
    res.json({ status: 'processing' });
  }
});
```

Frontend polls status endpoint until ready, then downloads.

Files:
- services/export/controller.js
- frontend/components/ExportButton.jsx

Changes:
- Added job status endpoint
- Frontend polls every 1s until complete
- Download triggered only after job completion
- Added progress indicator

**WORKAROUND:**
Wait 5 seconds after clicking export, then click download link in notification

---

**VERIFY:**

✓ Click export button
✓ See progress spinner
✓ Wait for "Ready to download" message
✓ Download file
✓ Verify file contains data

Success: CSV file contains all expected rows, proper formatting, no empty files

Test: Customers > Export > CSV → Wait for completion → Download → Open in Excel → Verify 1000+ rows

Timing: Export completes in 3-5 seconds for typical datasets

1202.description:
Service: Background Job Processor
Feature: Async Task Execution
Activity: Processing queued jobs

**ISSUE:**

Worker process memory grows from 200MB to 8GB over 24 hours. Process crashes with OOM error. Requires daily restart.

Error: "FATAL ERROR: CALL_AND_RETRY_LAST Allocation failed - JavaScript heap out of memory"

**SYMPTOMS:**
→ Memory usage increases steadily
→ Starts at 200MB, reaches 8GB in 24 hours
→ Process crashes around 2:00 AM daily
→ Jobs fail when worker crashes
→ Restart fixes issue temporarily
→ Memory profiling shows event listeners accumulating

**AFFECTED:**
Node.js worker process, job queue, event emitter

---

**ROOT CAUSE:**

Event listeners not removed after job completion. Each job added event listener but never cleaned up. After processing 10,000 jobs, 10,000 event listeners attached to same emitter.

```javascript
// BEFORE - Memory leak:
function processJob(job) {
  jobEmitter.on('complete', (result) => {
    console.log('Job completed:', result);
  });
  // Listener never removed!
  executeJob(job);
}
```

Node.js EventEmitter stores all listeners in memory. 10,000 listeners × 800KB per listener = 8GB memory.

**FIX:**

Properly remove event listeners:

```javascript
// AFTER - Fixed:
function processJob(job) {
  const completeHandler = (result) => {
    console.log('Job completed:', result);
  };

  jobEmitter.once('complete', completeHandler);  // Use 'once' instead of 'on'

  try {
    executeJob(job);
  } finally {
    // Explicit cleanup if needed
    jobEmitter.removeListener('complete', completeHandler);
  }
}
```

Also added memory monitoring:

```javascript
setInterval(() => {
  const usage = process.memoryUsage();
  console.log('Memory:', Math.round(usage.heapUsed / 1024 / 1024), 'MB');

  if (usage.heapUsed > 1024 * 1024 * 1024) {  // 1GB
    console.error('Memory threshold exceeded!');
    // Alert operations team
  }
}, 60000);
```

Files:
- workers/job-processor.js
- workers/monitoring.js

Changes:
- Changed .on() to .once() for one-time listeners
- Added explicit listener cleanup
- Implemented memory monitoring
- Added memory usage alerts

**WORKAROUND:**
Restart worker process daily via cron (not ideal)

---

**VERIFY:**

1. Start worker process
2. Monitor memory usage:
```bash
watch -n 10 'ps aux | grep worker-process'
```

3. Process 1000 test jobs:
```bash
./scripts/queue-test-jobs.sh --count=1000
```

4. Check memory after 1000 jobs:
- Should remain under 500MB
- Should not grow continuously

5. Let run for 24 hours
6. Verify memory stable (not growing)

Expected:
Memory usage stays under 500MB regardless of jobs processed. No continuous growth. No OOM crashes.

Test:
- Run worker for 24 hours
- Process 10,000+ jobs  
- Memory should remain stable

Timing: Monitor for 24 hours to confirm fix

1205.description:
Service: Product Search
Feature: Autocomplete Suggestions
Activity: Typing in search box

**PROBLEM:**

Autocomplete dropdown doesn't show suggestions while typing. API calls succeed and return results but dropdown remains empty.

No error message - just empty dropdown.

**SYMPTOMS:**
• Type in search box
• Dropdown appears but empty
• Network tab shows successful API calls
• API returns correct suggestions
• Dropdown shows "No results" despite API returning data
• Issue intermittent - sometimes works
• More likely to fail with fast typing

**COMPONENTS:**
Search autocomplete component, debounce function, React state

---

**ROOT CAUSE:**

Race condition in debounced search. Fast typing triggered multiple API calls. Responses arrived out of order. Older response overwrote newer results.

Sequence:
1. User types "pro"
2. API call 1 sent for "pro"
3. User types "d" → "prod"
4. API call 2 sent for "prod"
5. Response 2 arrives ("prod" results)
6. UI updates with "prod" results
7. Response 1 arrives late ("pro" results)
8. UI updates with "pro" results (wrong!)
9. User sees results for "pro" while input shows "prod"

**FIX:**

Implemented request cancellation:

```javascript
// BEFORE:
const debouncedSearch = debounce(async (query) => {
  const results = await searchAPI(query);
  setSuggestions(results);
}, 300);

// AFTER:
let currentRequest = null;

const debouncedSearch = debounce(async (query) => {
  // Cancel previous request
  if (currentRequest) {
    currentRequest.cancel();
  }

  // Create new request with cancel token
  currentRequest = axios.CancelToken.source();

  try {
    const results = await searchAPI(query, {
      cancelToken: currentRequest.token
    });
    setSuggestions(results);
  } catch (error) {
    if (!axios.isCancel(error)) {
      console.error(error);
    }
  }
}, 300);
```

Also added request ID tracking:

```javascript
let requestId = 0;

const debouncedSearch = debounce(async (query) => {
  const currentId = ++requestId;

  const results = await searchAPI(query);

  // Only update if this is still the latest request
  if (currentId === requestId) {
    setSuggestions(results);
  }
}, 300);
```

Files:
- frontend/components/SearchAutocomplete.jsx
- frontend/utils/debounce.js

Changes:
- Added request cancellation
- Implemented request ID tracking
- Ignore stale responses
- Added loading state management

**WORKAROUND:**
Type slowly and wait for suggestions to appear

---

**VERIFY:**

1. Open search box
2. Type quickly: "product"
3. Verify suggestions appear for "product"
4. Suggestions should match current input
5. No flickering or wrong suggestions

Test rapid typing:
1. Type: "p" → "pr" → "pro" → "prod" → "produ" → "product"
2. Type fast (< 100ms between characters)
3. Verify final suggestions match "product"
4. Check network tab - should see cancelled requests

Expected:
Suggestions always match current input. No race conditions. Stale responses ignored.

Test:
- Search box → Type "product" quickly → Suggestions should show products, not partial matches

Timing: Immediate

1211.description:
**INCIDENT**

🔐 Service: Authentication Service
🔐 Feature: OAuth Token Refresh
🔐 Activity: Refreshing expired access token

**PROBLEM:**

Users automatically logged out after 1 hour of activity. Token refresh fails with 401 error. Users must log in again. Issue affects all users.

Error: "401 Unauthorized - Invalid refresh token"

**OBSERVED:**
• Users logged out exactly after 1 hour
• First token refresh succeeds
• Second refresh fails
• Refresh token marked as used
• Token rotation enabled
• New refresh token not saved
• Issue started after security update

**AFFECTED:**
OAuth service, token storage, frontend session management

---

**ROOT CAUSE:**

OAuth server configured with refresh token rotation (security best practice). Each refresh returns new refresh token and invalidates old one. Frontend saved new access token but didn't update refresh token in storage.

Flow:
1. User logs in → Gets access token + refresh token A
2. After 1 hour, access token expires
3. Frontend refreshes using token A → Gets new access token + refresh token B
4. Frontend saves access token but keeps refresh token A
5. After another hour, tries to refresh using token A (already invalidated)
6. Server rejects (token A already used)

**FIX:**

Updated frontend to save new refresh token:

```javascript
// BEFORE:
async function refreshAccessToken() {
  const refreshToken = localStorage.getItem('refresh_token');

  const response = await fetch('/oauth/token', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify({
      grant_type: 'refresh_token',
      refresh_token: refreshToken
    })
  });

  const data = await response.json();
  localStorage.setItem('access_token', data.access_token);
  // BUG: Not saving new refresh token!
}

// AFTER:
async function refreshAccessToken() {
  const refreshToken = localStorage.getItem('refresh_token');

  const response = await fetch('/oauth/token', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: JSON.stringify({
      grant_type: 'refresh_token',
      refresh_token: refreshToken
    })
  });

  const data = await response.json();

  // Save both tokens
  localStorage.setItem('access_token', data.access_token);
  localStorage.setItem('refresh_token', data.refresh_token);

  return data.access_token;
}
```

Added error handling:

```javascript
try {
  await refreshAccessToken();
} catch (error) {
  if (error.status === 401) {
    // Refresh token invalid, force re-login
    localStorage.clear();
    window.location.href = '/login';
  }
}
```

Files:
- frontend/auth/token-manager.js
- frontend/api/interceptor.js

Changes:
- Save new refresh token after refresh
- Added error handling for invalid refresh token
- Implemented automatic retry logic
- Added token expiry monitoring

**WORKAROUND:**
Users must log in again every hour

---

**VERIFICATION:**

1. Login to application
2. Note current time
3. Wait 1 hour (or modify token expiry for testing)
4. Trigger API call that requires authentication
5. Verify token refreshes automatically
6. Check localStorage:
```javascript
localStorage.getItem('refresh_token')
// Should be different from initial token
```

7. Wait another hour
8. Trigger another API call
9. Verify still logged in (second refresh works)

Expected:
Users stay logged in indefinitely. Token refresh works multiple times. No forced logouts.

Test:
- Login → Wait 65 min → Make API call → Should succeed without re-login

Timing: Immediate

1212.description:
Service: Search Platform
Feature: Product Search
Activity: Full-text search queries

**ISSUE:**

Search queries extremely slow. Response time increased from 500ms to 15+ seconds. Users complaining about slow search. No recent code changes.

No error - just very slow responses.

**SYMPTOMS:**
→ Query response time: 500ms → 15 seconds
→ Affects all search queries
→ Elasticsearch CPU at 90%+
→ Index size: 50GB → 200GB in 2 weeks
→ Segment count: 1,000+
→ No recent application changes
→ Data volume increased 4x

**COMPONENTS:**
Elasticsearch cluster, product index, search queries

---

**ROOT CAUSE:**

Index not optimized after large data import. 4x increase in documents created 1,000+ small segments. Elasticsearch must search all segments for each query. Segment merging not keeping up with write rate.

Index stats:
- Documents: 10M → 40M
- Segments: 50 → 1,200
- Deleted docs: 5M (not purged)
- Merge policy: default (not aggressive enough)

**FIX:**

Force merge to reduce segments:

```bash
# 1. Reduce replica count (faster merging)
PUT /products/_settings
{
  "number_of_replicas": 0
}

# 2. Force merge to 1 segment per shard
POST /products/_forcemerge?max_num_segments=1

# 3. Restore replicas
PUT /products/_settings
{
  "number_of_replicas": 1
}
```

Optimized index settings:

```json
PUT /products/_settings
{
  "index": {
    "refresh_interval": "30s",
    "number_of_replicas": 1,
    "merge": {
      "policy": {
        "max_merged_segment": "5gb",
        "segments_per_tier": 10
      }
    },
    "translog": {
      "durability": "async",
      "sync_interval": "30s"
    }
  }
}
```

Added index lifecycle policy:

```json
PUT _ilm/policy/products-policy
{
  "policy": {
    "phases": {
      "hot": {
        "actions": {
          "rollover": {
            "max_size": "50gb",
            "max_age": "7d"
          },
          "forcemerge": {
            "max_num_segments": 1
          }
        }
      },
      "warm": {
        "min_age": "30d",
        "actions": {
          "shrink": {
            "number_of_shards": 1
          },
          "forcemerge": {
            "max_num_segments": 1
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Files:
- elasticsearch/index-settings.json
- elasticsearch/ilm-policy.json

Changes:
- Reduced segments: 1,200 → 5 per shard
- Optimized merge policy
- Increased refresh interval: 1s → 30s
- Implemented index lifecycle management
- Scheduled regular force merge

**WORKAROUND:**
Use filters to narrow search scope (reduces data scanned)

---

**VERIFY:**

1. Check segment count:
```bash
GET /products/_segments
# Should show < 10 segments per shard
```

2. Test query performance:
```bash
GET /products/_search
{
  "query": {
    "match": {"name": "motor"}
  }
}
# Check "took" field - should be < 1000ms
```

3. Monitor merge activity:
```bash
GET /_cat/nodes?v&h=name,merges.current,merges.total
```

4. Check index stats:
```bash
GET /products/_stats
# Verify deleted docs purged
```

Expected:
Query response time < 1 second. Segment count < 10 per shard. CPU usage normal. Deleted docs purged.

Test: Run search query 10 times → Average response time < 1s

Timing: Force merge takes 2-4 hours. Performance improves immediately after completion.

1218.description:
Service: GraphQL API
Feature: Nested Data Queries
Activity: Fetching users with their orders

**ISSUE:**

GraphQL queries with nested relationships extremely slow. Query for 100 users with their orders takes 45 seconds. Database shows 10,000+ queries executed. Classic N+1 problem.

No error - just very slow response.

**SYMPTOMS:**
→ Nested queries very slow (30-60 seconds)
→ Simple queries fast (< 100ms)
→ Database query count extremely high
→ 1 query for users + 100 queries for orders (N+1)
→ Connection pool exhausted
→ CPU normal, database I/O high
→ Started after adding order relationship

**COMPONENTS:**
GraphQL server, database, ORM, query resolvers

---

**ROOT CAUSE:**

GraphQL resolvers fetched related data individually for each parent record. Query for 100 users triggered:
- 1 query: SELECT * FROM users (100 results)
- 100 queries: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = ? (one per user)

Total: 101 queries instead of 2

Resolver code:

```javascript
// BEFORE - N+1 problem:
const resolvers = {
  User: {
    orders: (user) => {
      // Called once per user!
      return db.query(
        'SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id = ?',
        [user.id]
      );
    }
  }
};
```

**FIX:**

Implemented DataLoader for batching:

```javascript
// AFTER - Using DataLoader:
const DataLoader = require('dataloader');

// Batch function - loads orders for multiple users at once
const batchOrders = async (userIds) => {
  const orders = await db.query(
    'SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id IN (?)',
    [userIds]
  );

  // Group orders by user_id
  const ordersByUser = {};
  orders.forEach(order => {
    if (!ordersByUser[order.user_id]) {
      ordersByUser[order.user_id] = [];
    }
    ordersByUser[order.user_id].push(order);
  });

  // Return in same order as requested
  return userIds.map(id => ordersByUser[id] || []);
};

// Create DataLoader instance
const orderLoader = new DataLoader(batchOrders);

const resolvers = {
  User: {
    orders: (user) => {
      // DataLoader batches all requests in single tick
      return orderLoader.load(user.id);
    }
  }
};
```

Added query complexity analysis:

```javascript
const { createComplexityLimitRule } = require('graphql-validation-complexity');

const server = new ApolloServer({
  typeDefs,
  resolvers,
  validationRules: [
    createComplexityLimitRule(1000, {
      onCost: (cost) => {
        console.log('Query cost:', cost);
      }
    })
  ]
});
```

Implemented query depth limiting:

```javascript
const depthLimit = require('graphql-depth-limit');

const server = new ApolloServer({
  typeDefs,
  resolvers,
  validationRules: [
    depthLimit(5)  // Max 5 levels of nesting
  ]
});
```

Files:
- graphql/resolvers/user.js
- graphql/loaders/index.js
- graphql/server.js

Changes:
- Implemented DataLoader for all relationships
- Added query complexity limits
- Added query depth limits
- Implemented caching layer
- Added query performance monitoring

**WORKAROUND:**
Fetch users and orders separately, combine client-side

---

**VERIFY:**

1. Enable query logging:
```javascript
db.on('query', (query) => {
  console.log('SQL:', query);
});
```

2. Execute test query:
```graphql
query {
  users(limit: 100) {
    id
    name
    orders {
      id
      total
    }
  }
}
```

3. Count queries:
- Should see 2 queries total:
  - 1 for users
  - 1 for all orders (batched)

4. Measure response time:
- Should complete in < 1 second

5. Test with larger dataset:
```graphql
query {
  users(limit: 1000) {
    orders {
      items {
        product {
          category
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
# Should still complete quickly with batching
```

Expected:
Query executes in under 1 second. Database queries batched efficiently. No N+1 problem. 2-3 queries instead of 100+.

Test: Query 100 users with orders → Response in < 1s → 2 DB queries

Timing: Immediate

1229.description:
**INCIDENT**

💳 Service: Payment Processing
💳 Feature: Webhook Handler
💳 Activity: Processing payment confirmation webhooks

**PROBLEM:**

Stripe webhooks failing signature verification. All webhook requests rejected with 400 error. Payments succeed but order status not updated. Stripe dashboard shows webhook failures.

Error: "Webhook signature verification failed"

**OBSERVED:**
• All Stripe webhooks fail
• Signature verification returns false
• Payments process successfully
• Orders stuck in "pending" status
• Webhook endpoint returns 400
• Started after framework upgrade
• Body parser middleware added
• Raw request body not available

**AFFECTED:**
Stripe webhook endpoint, payment confirmation, order status updates

---

**ROOT CAUSE:**

Stripe signature verification requires raw request body. Framework upgrade added JSON body parser middleware. Body parser consumed request stream and parsed JSON. Signature verification received parsed object instead of raw bytes. Signature mismatch.

Signature verification:

```javascript
// BEFORE - After body parser:
app.use(express.json());  // Parses all JSON bodies

app.post('/webhook/stripe', (req, res) => {
    const sig = req.headers['stripe-signature'];

    try {
        // req.body is parsed object, not raw bytes!
        const event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(
            req.body,  // Wrong - this is parsed JSON
            sig,
            webhookSecret
        );
    } catch (err) {
        return res.status(400).send(`Webhook Error: ${err.message}`);
    }
});
```

**FIX:**

Preserved raw body for webhook endpoint:

```javascript
// AFTER - Raw body for webhooks:
const express = require('express');

app.post('/webhook/stripe',
    express.raw({type: 'application/json'}),  // Get raw body
    (req, res) => {
        const sig = req.headers['stripe-signature'];

        try {
            const event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(
                req.body,  // Now this is raw Buffer
                sig,
                process.env.STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET
            );

            // Process event
            handleStripeEvent(event);

            res.json({received: true});
        } catch (err) {
            console.error('Webhook signature verification failed:', err.message);
            return res.status(400).send(`Webhook Error: ${err.message}`);
        }
    }
);

// Use JSON parser for other routes
app.use(express.json());
```

Alternative - custom middleware:

```javascript
// Custom middleware to preserve raw body
app.use((req, res, next) => {
    if (req.originalUrl === '/webhook/stripe') {
        // Don't parse, keep raw
        next();
    } else {
        express.json()(req, res, next);
    }
});

app.post('/webhook/stripe', 
    express.raw({type: 'application/json'}),
    handleStripeWebhook
);
```

Added webhook testing:

```javascript
// Test webhook signature locally
const testWebhook = async () => {
    const payload = JSON.stringify({
        id: 'evt_test',
        type: 'payment_intent.succeeded'
    });

    const signature = stripe.webhooks.generateTestHeaderString({
        payload,
        secret: webhookSecret
    });

    const response = await fetch('http://localhost:3000/webhook/stripe', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: {
            'Content-Type': 'application/json',
            'Stripe-Signature': signature
        },
        body: payload
    });

    console.log('Status:', response.status);
};
```

Implemented webhook retry logic:

```javascript
const handleStripeEvent = async (event) => {
    // Idempotency check
    const existing = await db.webhookEvents.findOne({
        stripe_event_id: event.id
    });

    if (existing) {
        console.log('Event already processed:', event.id);
        return;
    }

    // Process based on event type
    switch (event.type) {
        case 'payment_intent.succeeded':
            await handlePaymentSuccess(event.data.object);
            break;
        case 'payment_intent.failed':
            await handlePaymentFailure(event.data.object);
            break;
    }

    // Record event as processed
    await db.webhookEvents.create({
        stripe_event_id: event.id,
        processed_at: new Date()
    });
};
```

Added monitoring:

```javascript
const webhookMetrics = {
    received: 0,
    verified: 0,
    failed: 0
};

app.post('/webhook/stripe', async (req, res) => {
    webhookMetrics.received++;

    try {
        const event = stripe.webhooks.constructEvent(/*...*/);
        webhookMetrics.verified++;

        await handleStripeEvent(event);
        res.json({received: true});
    } catch (err) {
        webhookMetrics.failed++;
        console.error('Webhook error:', err);
        res.status(400).send(`Webhook Error: ${err.message}`);
    }
});

app.get('/webhook/metrics', (req, res) => {
    res.json(webhookMetrics);
});
```

Files:
- app/routes/webhooks.js
- app/middleware/bodyParser.js
- tests/webhook.test.js
- monitoring/webhook-metrics.js

Changes:
- Use express.raw() for webhook endpoint
- Preserve raw request body
- Added idempotency checking
- Implemented webhook testing
- Added retry logic
- Implemented monitoring

**WORKAROUND:**
Manually update order status from Stripe dashboard

---

**VERIFICATION:**

1. Test with Stripe CLI:
```bash
stripe listen --forward-to localhost:3000/webhook/stripe
stripe trigger payment_intent.succeeded
# Should show successful verification
```

2. Check webhook endpoint:
```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/webhook/stripe \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -H "Stripe-Signature: test" \
  -d '{"type": "test"}'
# Should return 400 (invalid signature) not 500
```

3. Verify in Stripe dashboard:
- Go to Developers > Webhooks
- Check recent webhook attempts
- Should show 200 responses

4. Test payment flow:
```bash
# Create test payment
stripe payment_intents create \
  --amount=1000 \
  --currency=usd \
  --confirm=true

# Check order status updated
curl http://localhost:3000/api/orders/latest
# Should show status: "paid"
```

5. Monitor webhook metrics:
```bash
curl http://localhost:3000/webhook/metrics
# Should show verified > 0, failed = 0
```

Expected:
Webhook signature verification succeeds. Events processed. Order status updated. No 400 errors.

Test: Trigger test webhook → Verify 200 response → Check order updated

Timing: Immediate

1237.description:
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
INCIDENT
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Service: Real-time Communication
Feature: WebSocket Connections
Activity: Maintaining persistent connections

PROBLEM:
WebSocket connections dropping after exactly 60 seconds. Real-time updates stop working. Clients must reconnect. ELB terminating idle connections. Keepalive not configured.

Error in client: "WebSocket connection closed unexpectedly"

Symptoms:
- Connections drop at 60 seconds
- Affects all WebSocket connections
- No data transfer = connection closed
- ELB idle timeout: 60 seconds
- No ping/pong implemented
- Reconnection storm
- Started after migrating to ELB
- Classic Load Balancer used

Affected Components:
ELB, WebSocket server, client connections, idle timeout

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
RESOLUTION
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

ROOT CAUSE:

ELB idle timeout set to 60 seconds (default). WebSocket connections with no data transfer for 60 seconds terminated by ELB. Application didn't implement ping/pong keepalive. Real-time dashboard had periods of no updates.

Connection lifecycle:
1. Client connects via WebSocket
2. Initial data sent
3. No updates for 60 seconds (idle)
4. ELB closes connection (idle timeout)
5. Client disconnected
6. Client reconnects
7. Cycle repeats

RESOLUTION:

Increased ELB idle timeout:

```bash
# AWS CLI - Classic Load Balancer
aws elb modify-load-balancer-attributes \
  --load-balancer-name my-load-balancer \
  --load-balancer-attributes "{\"ConnectionSettings\":{\"IdleTimeout\":3600}}"

# Application Load Balancer
aws elbv2 modify-target-group-attributes \
  --target-group-arn arn:aws:elasticloadbalancing:... \
  --attributes Key=deregistration_delay.timeout_seconds,Value=3600
```

Implemented WebSocket ping/pong:

```javascript
// Server-side (Node.js)
const WebSocket = require('ws');

const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 });

const PING_INTERVAL = 30000; // 30 seconds
const PONG_TIMEOUT = 5000; // 5 seconds

wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
    ws.isAlive = true;

    // Handle pong responses
    ws.on('pong', () => {
        ws.isAlive = true;
    });

    // Send ping every 30 seconds
    const pingInterval = setInterval(() => {
        if (ws.isAlive === false) {
            // Client didn't respond to ping
            clearInterval(pingInterval);
            return ws.terminate();
        }

        ws.isAlive = false;
        ws.ping();
    }, PING_INTERVAL);

    ws.on('close', () => {
        clearInterval(pingInterval);
    });
});
```

Client-side keepalive:

```javascript
// Client-side
class WebSocketClient {
    constructor(url) {
        this.url = url;
        this.reconnectInterval = 5000;
        this.connect();
    }

    connect() {
        this.ws = new WebSocket(this.url);

        this.ws.onopen = () => {
            console.log('Connected');
            this.startHeartbeat();
        };

        this.ws.onclose = () => {
            console.log('Disconnected, reconnecting...');
            this.stopHeartbeat();
            setTimeout(() => this.connect(), this.reconnectInterval);
        };

        this.ws.onerror = (error) => {
            console.error('WebSocket error:', error);
        };

        this.ws.onmessage = (event) => {
            this.handleMessage(event.data);
        };
    }

    startHeartbeat() {
        this.heartbeatInterval = setInterval(() => {
            if (this.ws.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
                // Send heartbeat
                this.ws.send(JSON.stringify({ type: 'ping' }));
            }
        }, 30000); // 30 seconds
    }

    stopHeartbeat() {
        if (this.heartbeatInterval) {
            clearInterval(this.heartbeatInterval);
        }
    }
}
